Dear Newbie:

I feel like writing a bit, so let me give this a shot.

As a general rule, I think that Decency trumps the Law. I'm not quite
sure why I feel this way. Maybe it is because we have to live with
ourselves and decency is always a nice thing to have on your side and
living inside yourself.

Putting off the divorce until the I-751 process is complete is the
decent thing to do.

And yet, I must say that I have handled several matters where things
were put off until after the I-751 has been completed. And this has
always come to grief for the US Citizen spouse, (divorce-wise, the
shorter the term of the marriage the better).

I'm not sure why this would be so...it seems counter-intuitive to me,
but this has been my experience. On the other hand, I only see things
when they go bad. This may go on quite a bit and it works out well for
the parties involved but I just never get to see it because it is done
on an entirely amicable basis.

This is entirely your call, your decision. I don't believe that your
wife has a choice if you file for divorce or not. You just do it.

How to weigh out these factors is difficult...but if there is NO
chance of reconciliation, no chance that counseling or some other
thing might help save this marriage...

Then I'll bite the bullet and tell you to just file the divorce and
let the chips fall where they may.

Tough advice...but there it is.

Best Wishes,

Traveller

